     DESAI, J.	We are	not inclined to grant special leave,
but we	make this  short speaking order in order to keep the
record straight	 that the  dismissal of	 the  special  leave
petition does  not tentamount  to affirmance of the order of
the learned  Judge of the High Court who for reasons utterly
untenable interfered with teh
215
sentence imposed  by the  trial	 court	and  reduced  it  to
sentence  already   undergone  which   in  the	 facts	 and
circumstances of the case was wholly impermissible.
 In Meet Singh v. State of Punjab,(1) this Court pointed
out that  Sec. 5(2)  of the  Prevention	 of  Corruption	 Act
prescribes a minimum sentence and discretion is conferred on
the court  to give  less than  the minimum  for any  special
reasons to  be recorded in writing. This Court examined what
constitute special  reasons for the purpose of Sec. 5(2) and
pointed out  that the reasons which weighed with the learned
Judge in  reducing the	sentence to  the sentence  undergone
could not  be special  reasons. Therefore,  in our view, the
learned Judge  was entirely  in error in showing a misplaced
sympathy unsustainable	in law.	 With these  observations we
reject the special leave petition.
N.V.K.					 Petition dismissed.
